Introduction¶

Data came from 2 files on the EPA website that detailed fuel economy from 2020-2021 vehicles driven in the United States.
2020 EPA Vehicle Dataset: https://www.epa.gov/sites/default/files/2021-03/20tstcar-2021-03-02.xlsx
2021 EPA Vehicle Dataset: https://www.epa.gov/system/files/documents/2021-08/21tstcar-2021-08-25.xlsx

Constraints for Vehicle Dataset¶


  • The data to be analyzed will be from the 2020 and 2021 EPA vehicle data set.
  • Unecessary columns will be removed from dataset to keep things clean.
  • If the values in the adjusted fuel economy is not a number, those records will be deleted. The main purpose of this research is to look at the relationship between transmission design and fuel economy. Visually, most of the NaN(not a number) values were from fully electric vehicles that did not get tested for fuel economy for some reason.
  • Analysis will be limited to vehicles that either run off of diesel, gasoline, or partial hybrid (combustion engine with battery power). All vehicles that are fully electric that do not run off of diesel or gasoline will be discarded.
  • Any extreme outlier values for adjusted fuel economy will be removed, as these are errors. Based on a visual inspection of all the data in the CSV file, I removed records where MPG is above 84.5 and below 8 mpg. Anything above 84.5 mpg was related to fully electric vehicles, and anything below about 8mpg is not a valid fuel economy value
  • A focus will be kept strictly on the relationship between transmission design (the number of gears in the transmission) and adjusted fuel economy.

    Columns of Interest - Variable Types¶


  • Number Gears - this is a categorical number with an ordinal value. Gears go from 1 speed to 10 speed. This will be the independent variable.

  • Adjusted Fuel Economy - gives numerical value of fuel economy for each vehicle tested; give in miles per gallon. This is a continuous variable and will be used as the dependent variable in any modeling

  • Model Year - discrete value, either 2020 or 2021

  • Test Veh Displacement (L) - this is numerical and relates to the size of the engine displacement. Usually, a normal combustion based engine will have an engine displacement of at least 1 liter (L) or higher.

  • Test Fuel Type Description - gives a description of the type of fuel used. This is used to filter out certain constraints.

  • Test Category - gives the type of vehicle test used by the EPA

    In [21]:
    # Clean fuel economy values by processing with boolean masking. 

# Step 1:
# Used boolean masking.  Keep any record that has a mpg of less than 84.5 mpg.
car_df = car_df[car_df['Adjusted Fuel Economy'] <= 84.5]

# Step 2:
# Keep any record that has a mpg greater than 8 mpg.
car_df = car_df[car_df['Adjusted Fuel Economy'] >= 8.0]

# Step 3:
# Keep records that are not related to having a full electric vehicle (See constraints section)
car_df = car_df[car_df['Test Fuel Type Description'] != 'Electricity']

# Step 4: 
# Keep records that are not related to having a full electric vehicle (See constraints section)
car_df = car_df[car_df['Test Veh Displacement (L)'] > 1.00]

    Data Cleaning: Cut rows that have fuel economy values that are outliers. Visually inspected CSV dataset files. Any values over 84.5mpg were mainly related to full electric vehicles or other errors. Any fuel economy values less than 8mpg were also errors. For example, havinga fuel economy of 0 mpg is not feasible. Removed all records if fuel type was full electric.¶

    Key Conclusions¶

    Research Question:¶

    To what extent do the total number of gears in the transmission have on fuel economy (FE) for vehicles driven in the United States that were produced from 2020-2021?</u>

    Key conclusions based on Data Analysis:¶

  • There were about as many 2020 models tested as there were 2021 models.


  • 8 speed transmissions were the most popular.


  • 1 speed, 5 speed (low sample size), 6 speed, and 8 speed transmissions provided the best adjusted fuel economy.


  • Variance in values was higher for vehicles using diesel fuel as opposed to gasoline (or gasoline/electric partial hybrid).


  • Most FE values were between 15 and 50 mpg for all vehicles tested.


  • 6 speed and 8 speed transmissions do have some outlier values.


  • There is a negative correlation between transmission design and FE.


  • All modeling tests for transmission design versus adjusted FE showed a p-value of 0.


  • Slope coefficient was negative for the linear equation model.


  • Since p values were 0 and slope coefficient was negative (and not 0), reject null hypothesis.


  • Accept alternative hypothesis: there is an impact between transmission design and FE.


    • Key conclusions for Legend's Business Needs:¶

  • There is an impact between transmission design and FE.


  • 1 speed, 6 speed, and 8 speed transmissions provided the best adjusted fuel economy.


  • Given FE and popularity of use, 1 speed CVT transmissions are suited well for improving FE in the Alanty model; this is especially due to their lightweight design and reduced cost.


  • 8 speed transmissions provide stable FE numbers and are built for stable FE.


  • 5 speed transmissions had good FE numbers but sample size was too low, 60.


  • 6 speed transmissions had good FE numbers but had a number of outliers which inflated average mpg values.


  • Performing further analysis would be beneficial to see if a CVT transmission would be beneficial for FE and customer satisfaction.
